        "title": "Operating Limit Speeds",
        "content": "In service an aircraft must observe certain speed limitations. These may be maximum speeds or minimum speeds, but in each case they are set to give safe operation in the prevailing conditions. The limits may be set by various considerations, the main ones being: strength of the aircraft structure, stiffness of the aircraft structure, and adequate control of the aircraft.\n\nStrength is the ability of the structure to withstand a load, and stiffness is the ability to withstand deformation."
      },
      {
        "title": "Loads and Safety Factors",
        "content": "Limit load: The maximum load to be expected in service.\nUltimate load: The failing load of the structure.\nFactor of safety: The ratio of ultimate load to limit load.\nFor aircraft structures the factor of safety is 1.5. The safety factor on aircraft structures is much lower than the safety factors used in other forms of engineering because of the extreme importance of minimum weight in aircraft structures."
      },
      {
        "title": "Load Factor and Manoeuvre Envelope",
        "content": "The loads which must be considered are given in the design requirements of an aircraft. They are given in terms of load factor (n), colloquially known as 'g'.\nLoad Factor (n) = Lift / Weight.\nIn level flight, since lift equals weight, the load factor is 1.0 (1g).\nThe limit load is given in terms of load factor to make the requirement general to all aircraft.\nFor normal category aircraft, the positive limit load factor may not be less than 2.5 and need not be more than 3.8. The positive limit load factor for modern high speed jet transport aircraft is 2.5.\nFor utility category aircraft the positive limit load factor is 4.4.\nFor aerobatic category aircraft the positive limit load factor is 6.0.\nThe negative limit load factor may not be less than -1.0 for normal category aircraft."
      },
      {
        "title": "Design Speeds",
        "content": "Design Manoeuvring Speed (VA): The highest speed at which sudden, full elevator deflection (nose-up) can be made without exceeding the design limit load factor. VA = VS1g x Square Root of n.\n\nDesign Cruising Speed (VC): The speed at which the aircraft is designed to cruise efficiently.\n\nDesign Dive Speed (VD): The maximum speed which has to be demonstrated in flight when diving to the limit. VD must be at least 25% greater than VC.\n\nMaximum Operating Speed (VMO/MMO): VMO is a speed that may not be deliberately exceeded in any regime of flight (climb, cruise or descent). VMO must not be greater than VC and must be sufficiently below VD to make it highly improbable that VD will be exceeded. MMO (maximum operating Mach number) limits the aircraft at high altitudes.\n\nNever Exceed Speed (VNE): VNE is set below VD to allow for speed upsets to be recovered. VNE = 0.9 x VD."
      },
      {
        "title": "Gust Loads and Operational Limits",
        "content": "Gust Loads: The aircraft must be strong enough to withstand a vertical gust of 50 ft/sec at the design cruise speed VC and 25 ft per second at the design dive speed VD.\nOperational Rough-air Speed (VRA/MRA): The speed below which the aircraft should be flown to minimise exposure to rough air loads.\nLanding Gear Speed Limitations: The landing gear extended limit speed (VLE) must not be deliberately exceeded with the landing gear extended.\nFlap Speed Limit: The flap extended speed (VFE) is the maximum speed at which flaps may be extended."
      },
      {
        "title": "Aeroelasticity",
        "content": "Aeroelasticity (Aeroelastic Coupling): Aerodynamic forces acting on the aircraft produce distortion of the structure, and this distortion produces corresponding elastic forces in the structure. Structural distortion produces additional aerodynamic loading and this process is continued until either an equilibrium condition is reached or structural failure occurs.\nElasticity: No structure is perfectly rigid. The structure of an aircraft is designed to be as light as possible.\nBacklash: The possibility of movement of the control surface without any movement of the pilot's controls.\nMass distribution: The position of the CG of a surface in relation to its torsional axis.\nMass balance: A mass located to change the position of the CG of a surface in relation to its torsional axis.\nDivergence: The structure will continue to distort until it breaks. Aerodynamic force is proportional to V2, but structural torsional stiffness remains constant. At some high speed, the aerodynamic force build-up may overpower the resisting torsional stiffness and divergence will occur."
      },
{
        "title": "Flutter and Control Surface Flutter",
        "content": "Flutter: The rapid and uncontrolled oscillation of an aircraft or control surface. Flutter is caused by the interaction of aerodynamic, elastic and inertia forces. Flutter may be prevented by designing for stiffness and by mass balancing the control surfaces. Flutter can exist in a number of modes: wing torsion/flutter, aileron flutter, elevator flutter, and tailplane flutter.\nControl Surface Flutter: At high speeds, aerodynamic loads on a control surface may cause it to deflect. This deflection changes the stiffness and aerodynamic balance, producing a divergent oscillation. Flutter may also be caused by free play in the control system. Mass balance weights prevent control surface flutter by bringing the centre of gravity forward to a position on, or slightly in front of the hinge line.\nAileron Reversal: At high speeds, the ailerons can produce a roll in the opposite direction to that required. This is called aileron reversal and is caused by wing torsional flexibility."
