    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Introduction and Definition",
        "content": "Windshear is a sudden drastic shift in wind speed and/or direction that occurs over a short distance at any altitude in a vertical and/or horizontal plane. It can subject an aircraft to sudden updraughts, downdraughts or extreme horizontal wind components, causing sudden loss of lift or violent changes in vertical speeds or altitudes. Windshear will cause abrupt displacement from the flight path and require substantial control action to counteract it.\nA windshear encounter is a very dynamic event which can strike suddenly and with devastating effect. The first and most vital defence is avoidance. The most powerful examples of windshear are associated with thunderstorms (cumulonimbus clouds), but windshear can also be experienced in association with other meteorological features such as the passage of a front, or a marked low-level temperature inversion."
      },
      {
        "title": "Microburst",
        "content": "Microbursts are associated with thunderstorms and are one of the most dangerous sources of windshear. Microbursts are small-scale intense downdraughts which, on reaching the surface, spread outward in all directions from the downdraught centre. This causes the presence of both vertical and horizontal windshear that can be extremely hazardous to all types and sizes of aircraft, especially when within 1000 feet of the ground.\nA microburst downdraught is typically less than 1 mile in diameter as it descends from the cloud base to about 1000 to 3000 feet above the ground. In the transition zone near the ground, the downdraught changes to a horizontal outflow that can extend to approximately 2.5 miles (4 km) in diameter.\nDowndraughts can be as strong as 6000 feet per minute. Outflow winds can exceed 100 knots. The life cycle of a microburst is typically about 10-20 minutes from birth to decay."
      },
      {
        "title": "Windshear Encounter during Approach",
        "content": "During approach and landing, windshear may be encountered producing a headwind, tailwind or downdraught component.\nA decreasing headwind (tailwind shear) results in loss of airspeed and lift. The aircraft tends to sink and requires increased pitch attitude and thrust to maintain the approach path.\nAn increasing headwind produces a gain in airspeed and lift. The aircraft tends to climb and requires reduced pitch attitude and thrust to maintain the approach path.\nA downdraught will cause the aircraft to descend below the desired path requiring pitch attitude and thrust corrections.\nThe most dangerous situation for an aircraft on approach is a combination of a downdraught and a decreasing headwind."
      },
      {
        "title": "Effects of Windshear",
        "content": "On encountering windshear, the aircraft's flight path will be changed abruptly. The aircraft will encounter conditions which may be outside its normal operating envelope.\nWindshear will cause abrupt displacement from the flight path and require substantial control action to counteract it. The immediate effect on the aircraft is a change in airspeed.\nA decreasing headwind causes loss of airspeed - the aircraft tends to sink. An increasing headwind causes gain of airspeed - the aircraft tends to climb.\nThe pilot should apply maximum thrust and maintain the attitude appropriate to the IAS required at the barrier. The pitch attitude should not be forced down to restore the flight path, as this will further unload the wing. The aircraft should be flown at the recommended approach speed plus any additions for windshear."
      },
      {
        "title": "Recovery Techniques",
        "content": "The recommended recovery technique is to recognise the windshear and apply maximum thrust while maintaining the attitude appropriate to the indicated airspeed required at the barrier. The pitch attitude should not be forced down to restore the flight path, as this will further unload the wing. The aircraft should be flown at the recommended approach speed plus any additions for windshear.\nIf the aircraft becomes airborne during the recovery, it should be allowed to accelerate to the recommended climb speed before attempting to climb away. Once clear of the windshear layer, normal operations can be resumed to land.\nIf windshear is encountered on the runway during the take-off run, the take-off should be abandoned if the airspeed is below V1."
      },
      {
        "title": "Visual Clues and Reporting",
        "content": "Visual Clues: Some windshear events may be preceded by certain visual clues. On the ground, dust bowls, rain shafts or virga may be visible. An abrupt change in visibility may also indicate a windshear boundary. At night, the approach lighting may change in appearance if the aircraft is flying through an area of differing refractive index caused by the change in air density.\nWindshear Reporting: Pilots are requested to report windshear encounters to ATC to enable subsequent aircraft to be warned. Reports should include the altitude at which it was encountered and whether it was during climb, cruise or descent/approach."
      }
    ]
  }
